ntemporary citizens. Confronting head-on many of the beliefs we hold dear but seldom question, Samons examines Athens's history in the fifth and fourth centuries B.C. in order to test the popular idea that majority rule leads to good government. Challenging many basic assumptions about the character and success of Athenian democracy, What's Wrong with Democracy? offers fascinating and accessible discussions of topics including the dangers of the popular vote, Athens's acquisitive foreign policy, the tendency of the state to overspend, the place of religion in Athenian society, and more. Sure to generate controversy, Samons's bold and iconoclastic book finds that democracy has begun to function like an unacknowledged religion in our culture, immune from criticism and dissent, and he asks that we remember the Athenian example and begin to question our uncritical worship of democratic values such as freedom, choice, and diversity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDemocracyxHistory. 0aDirect democracyzGreecezAthens. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRepresentative government and representationzUnited States. 0aRepublicanismzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aamerican government.  aancient greece.  aathenian democracy.  aathenian government.  aathenian society.  achoice.  aclassical athenian democracy.  ademocracy.  ademocratic governments.  adissent.  adiversity.  aelections.  aforeign policy.  afreedom.  agovernment and governing.  agovernment and religion.  agovernment.  ahistorical.  ahistory.  anational defense.  apeloponnesian war.  apolitical systems.  apolitical theory.  apolitics.  apopular vote.  apublic finance.  aqualifications for citizenship.  areligion.  aunited states of america.  avo